C. Australia ex Philippines; Taiwan ex Philippines
Date: Thu 5 Mar 2020 5:33:43 PM PHT
Source: CNN Philippines [edited]
https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/5/Woman-who-traveled-to-Philippines-tests-positive-coronavirus-Australia-.html


Two people who traveled to the Philippines tested positive for coronavirus disease [COVID-19] after returning to Taiwan and Australia.

A man in his 30s went home to northern Taiwan on [3 Mar 2020] after a 5-day trip to the Philippines with his friends. The Taiwan Centers for Disease Control reported that the man had diarrhea in the Philippines on [2 Mar 2020] and went to the clinic for dry throat and tiredness after returning to Taiwan. The man's COVID-19 infection was confirmed by a laboratory test on [5 Mar 2020], Taiwan CDC added. He is Taiwan's 44th confirmed case of the disease caused by the novel coronavirus.

Meanwhile, a woman who traveled from the Philippines tested positive for coronavirus disease in Australia. The woman in her 60s returned to the south eastern state of New South Wales from the Philippines on [3 Mar 2020] and is one of 6 new confirmed COVID-19 cases across the state's capital Sydney, the local government there reported. She boarded Cebu Pacific flight 5J39 from the Philippines, it added. "Her travel details are being obtained and will be disclosed if she posed a risk to any other passengers on her flight," read a statement posted Wednesday [4 Mar 2020] in the NSW government website.

With the new addition, the total number of COVID-19 cases in NSW has risen to 22, it added. Australia has at least 43 confirmed cases of COVID-19 based on the World Health Organization's tally.

There are no reported cases yet of local transmission in the Philippines. The 3 confirmed cases recorded were all Chinese nationals who came from Wuhan City in China, the epicenter of the outbreak.

--
communicated by:
Ryan McGinnis
<ryan@digicana.com>

[The Philippines have reported 3 imported cases of COVID-19 and to date no local transmission. While the case from Taiwan was only in the Philippines for 5 days and could have had transmission in Taiwan prior to leaving for the Philippines, the case reported by Australia seems to have been in the Philippines during a full incubation period. - Mod.MPP

