B. France, situation update
Date: 5 Mar 2020
Source: The local
https://www.thelocal.fr/20200305/latest-number-of-coronavirus-cases-in-france-rises-to-130


The number of coronavirus cases in France continued to rise as health authorities on Thursday [5 Mar 2020] confirmed a total of 423 cases since the outbreak began in January [2020] -- with 138 newly diagnosed in the past 24 hours. 3 more people died of the illness, including a 73 year old from the Oise department and a 64 year old originally from the nearby Aisne department. 23 of those infected with the virus were currently in a 'serious' condition, said French health chief Jérôme Salomon on Thursday [5 Mar 2020] evening during the government's evening press conference. "This is the time to protect our weakest," Salomon said, reiterating that the people who had died from the virus so far, were all elderly with "serious underlying conditions".

Salomon said France was currently experiencing a situation similar to that of its neighbour Italy, where 41 people had died in 24 hours bringing the death toll to 148. "The elderly must benefit from the solidarity of the whole country;" the health chief said and urged people to take the necessary precautions to contain the contagion. "We want to limit and delay the peak of the epidemic," Salomon said.

Authorities also confirmed that cases have now been reported in all regions of mainland France -- although the highest numbers remain concentrated in 4 'cluster zones' - Mulhouse in the Haut-Rhin department in eastern France, Oise in the north east (55 cases), Morbihan (20 cases) in Brittany, and Haute-Savoie in the Alps (44 cases). A 5th cluster was a tour group that had travelled to Egypt, with 13 people testing positive for the infection.

France is still in 'stage 2', according to French health authorities. But French president Emmanuel Macron said stage 3 -- a full-blown epidemic -- was "inevitable". Macron was meeting on Thursday [5 Mar 2020] with top researchers leading the efforts to fight an outbreak that has seen authorities close around 150 schools. France would reach stage 3 in 1 or 2 weeks, according to these specialists. "Slowing the spread will dampen the impact on the population when we go to level 3, and limit the epidemic's peak," the health ministry said.

Measures to contain the virus in France were stepped up this week. Public gatherings of more than 5000 people in enclosed spaces have been banned alongside all public gatherings in the worst affected departments. On Monday [2 Mar 2020] British Airways announced that it is cutting some of its flights to France. Public health announcements in a variety of languages are also being broadcast on public transport systems including the Metro.

On Thursday [5 Mar 2020], Paris metro operator RATP reported that a station agent had tested positive for the virus, and had worked for several days before being hospitalised. A RATP union official said the woman had taken part in an evangelical rally last month [February 2020] in the eastern city of Mulhouse (Haut-Rhin), where officials have said several other participants had come down with the disease.

Government spokeswoman Sibeth Ndiaye said it per today was "out of the question to postpone the upcoming municipal elections" on [15 and 22 Mar 2020]. "We will take the necessary precautions," Ndiaye said after a cabinet meeting on Wednesday [4 Mar 2020] These measures could include distributing hand sanitiser at polling booths and avoiding crowded lines, Ndiaye said.

The Paris Marathon, which was due to take place on [5 Apr 2020], has reportedly been postponed until October [2020]. The Louvre museum, which had been closed since Sunday [1 Mar 2020], reopened its doors to visitors on Wednesday [4 Mar 2020]. In a press statement, the museum management said its "absolute priority" was to "ensure the security of its employees and visitors". The Paris Opéra on Wednesday [4 Mar 2020] asked people with "flu-like symptoms" to avoid both its venues, Garnier and Bastille, as a "precautionary measure".

French president Emmanuel Macron has cancelled his normal schedule to deal with the outbreak (and not, the Elysée Palace rushed to reassure people, because he has coronavirus himself). The total death toll in France now 7. An elderly Chinese tourist and a 60 year old French teacher also from the Compiègne area were the 1st 2 fatalities. Since then an 89 year old woman died at a hospital in Compiègne in northern France before the death of the 92 year old Brittany man brought the total to 4 before the 3 deaths were reported on Thursday [5 Mar 2020].

Germany has a similar number of cases to France but Italy is by the far the country in Europe most affected by the coronavirus outbreak after a huge surge in reported cases on Sunday [1 Mar 2020].

French ministers have also warned against all non-essential travel -- especially outside the EU -- and advised people in France to stop shaking hands and doing la bise (greeting with a kiss on each cheek) in an attempt to control the infection. But transport minister Elisabeth Borne said earlier this week that there was "no question of stopping trains from running" because of the virus.

The government has requisitioned the country's stocks of masks to distribute to health professionals and people self-isolating, in a bid to stop people from panic buying and creating shortages for those who need them. "Masks are indispensable in hospitals," health minister Véran said on Wednesday [4 Mar 2020]. But for people who were neither health workers nor contaminated by the virus, using masks was "pointless", Véran said. Fears of catching the virus have sparked a run on masks as well as sanitising hand gel in France, leading some stores and online retailers to hike prices. The price of hand sanitser has now been capped by government decree a €3 [USD 3.9] per 100ml.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The media report above gives a nice summary of the current situation in France, and a well balanced alert that France may well follow the path of Italy. Media reports of imported cases with a history of travel from France are increasing on a daily basis, a circumstantial bit of evidence that transmission is ongoing and growing. All regions of the country are reporting cases.

Panic over the COVID-19 seems to be almost universal in most countries with social media feeding into it as well as sensationalist media and sensationalist politics. Reports of hoarding of supplies such as hand sanitizer and face masks with price gouging [exploitative price increases] are not just from France. A good check in your country is to go on Amazon and see the price of hand sanitizers, and face masks. Face masks are critical for PPE (personal protective equipment) used by health professionals and country supplies need to be maintained. Local hypermarkets are running out of stocks of basics including bottled water (what's wrong with tap water in many of these countries?). Shortages are manmade and feed into the panic. If only rational risk communication was consistently provided....sigh. - Mod.MPP]

